% parrot0 WORLD FACTS — curated category membership as KNOWLEDGE, not C literals.
%
% gen230 (LLMSCORE behavioural resemblance). An LLM trivially "names a color that
% starts with B"; parrot0 can too, the honest KB-first way — the members live here
% as facts, and mod_namestart (20-math.c) reads the category + the target initial
% and returns the first known member. Add a category_member fact and the capability
% extends for free; nothing is hardcoded in C.
%
% NB: geography (capitals) was intentionally NOT added here — the `capital`
% predicate is owned by the curated analogy/fewshot/blankwall reasoning tests, which
% TEACH it at runtime; preloading base capital facts pollutes that machinery. So
% "capital of <country>" remains an honest, teachable gap for now.
%
% Members are single lowercase tokens (matching the canonicalized turn). Loaded
% KB_BASE and filtered from the user-fact count (is_internal_pred), so they are
% base substrate, never counted as facts the user taught.





% --- gen231: antonyms for "what's the opposite of <X>?" — answered by the existing
% gen11 relational query path (opposite(X, Y)). Stored BOTH directions (one clause
% per line: the .p0 reader is line-oriented) so the query always resolves. ---
% --- gen240 (LLMSCORE): more common antonyms (both directions).
% --- gen254: character/abstract antonyms (LLMSCORE probes vocabulary breadth) ---

% --- gen254: defining-phrase vocabulary — word_for(KeyPhrase, Word). The phrase
% is matched as a substring of the turn (like idiom_meaning), so "what word
% describes a person who always tells the truth?" resolves without quoting.
% Teaching a new entry is one fact, no code edit. ---
% gen311 (LLMSCORE): broaden the definition->word vocabulary (a common draw).

% --- gen240 (LLMSCORE): known-fact counting. quantity(Entity, Unit, N) reifies
% "an Entity has N Unit" — answered by the recall parser in 25-wordmath-reasoning.c
% for "how many <unit> does a <entity> have" and "how many <unit> are in a <entity>".
% The lexicon grows with facts; the engine is fixed.
% gen311 (LLMSCORE): more polygon sides, 3D-solid edges/faces/vertices, common counts.

% --- gen231: canonical colours of familiar things for "what color is a banana?"
% (mod_knowledge recognizer queries color_of/2). One ground colour each; a thing
% with several real colours just records its prototypical one, honestly partial. ---

% --- gen232 (LLMSCORE #5): causal sentence-completion knowledge. "complete this
% sentence: the sky is blue because..." / "why is the sky blue?" -> the reason from
% because/2. The key is the content words of the clause joined subject_adjective
% (sky_blue); the value is the reason clause (quoted, may contain commas). This is
% a completion grounded in KNOWLEDGE; an unknown clause is admitted, not invented. ---

% --- gen233 (kb-first manifesto, worked example #4): QUALITATIVE-CHANGE reasoning.
% grows_with(Feature, Base): Feature increases when Base's size increases (co-monotone;
% chained transitively in C). increases(Action, Source): the action makes more Source.
% Together they let "if knowledge is like a circle, what happens to its circumference
% when you learn?" be DEDUCED (more knowledge -> bigger circle -> bigger circumference),
% not generated. See docs/plans/kb-first.md. ---

% --- gen235 (LLMSCORE): common geography separated from teachable capital/2.
% `capital/2` remains available for analogy/few-shot learning; direct world
% questions use this curated substrate first.
% gen310: autolearn spill absorbed into world facts

% --- gen240 (LLMSCORE): one famous landmark per country, for compound
% "capital of X and a famous landmark there" questions. The phrase is KB
% knowledge; the C only selects by country.

% gen240 (LLMSCORE): reverse lookup — a landmark's city, keyed by a distinctive
% word in its name. "What city is the Eiffel Tower in?" -> Paris.

% --- gen240 (LLMSCORE): solar-system superlatives. planet_superlative(Property,
% Planet, "descriptive phrase") is the knowledge; the C maps a cue word in the
% question to the Property and reads the phrase (engine fixed, lexicon grows).

% gen251: broader world superlatives. world_superlative(Property, Domain,
% "answer") keeps stable open-world facts as data while the C only maps query
% tokens onto property/domain slots.

% --- gen239 (kb-first manifesto): island nations have no land-bordering
% countries. Explicit negative fact — closed-world absence would have implied
% "I don't know" rather than "zero"; we want the certitude behind a real
% curated claim, exactly as for `borders/2`. Substrate (is_struct_pred +
% is_internal_pred), so it never contaminates "how many facts do you know?". ---

% --- gen239 (kb-first manifesto): paint/colour mixing as KNOWLEDGE, not a C
% literal. Symmetric commutative pairs are stored both directions (the .p0
% reader is line-oriented) so mixes_to(X, Y, Z) resolves regardless of order. A
% new pair is DATA: add a fact and the mix recognizer (mod_knowledge) extends
% with no code edit. ---
% gen240 (LLMSCORE): purpose relation for analogies ("book is to reading as fork
% is to ___" -> eating). Left non-substrate so mod_analogy (which skips internal
% predicates) can use it as the linking relation.

% gen240 (LLMSCORE): a comparable MAGNITUDE relation, so "which is larger/closer:
% A or B?" is answered by comparing ranks (not pre-cooked answers). magnitude(Dim,
% Item, Rank) — only the order within a Dim matters.

% gen314: first-class measurements. measure(Dim, Entity, Value, Unit) is for
% physical/statistical quantities; compare_cue maps a question word to the
% dimension and direction. This stays separate from legacy magnitude/3 rankings.
% gen310a: length/river superlatives
% category link so the superlative consumer's "river" filter matches the_nile
% ("which river is the longest?" -> The_nile). NB: the "what is the longest
% river?" phrasing is still intercepted upstream (engine ordering gap).

% gen311: PAIR superlatives. pair_magnitude(Dim, A, B, Value) is a symmetric
% relation between two entities with a comparable value; the superlative consumer
% answers "which two X share the longest/shortest <Dim>?" with the extremum pair.
% Stored ONCE per pair (answer order is immaterial). Grow via autolearn
% (pair_magnitude is whitelisted). International land borders, length in km.

% gen251: city-to-city separation used by relative-motion frames. Values are
% ordinary road/rail-scale miles, rounded because the prompt itself is rounded.
% gen310a: organ size for superlative filtering

% gen250: contrast facts for the generic "difference between X and Y" frame.

% gen240 (LLMSCORE): animal sounds. "what sound does a dog make?" -> woof.

% gen254: ADDITIVE light mixing (RGB), distinct from pigment.
% gen254: the medium an artist works on — completes "painter is to canvas as
% sculptor is to ..." through the generic analogy engine (any R(A,B) works).

% --- gen239/240 (kb-first manifesto): land borders as a RELATION. The list
% handlers ("name three countries that border X", "neighbours of X") and the
% "which country borders both X and Y" query both INFER from borders/2 — no
% pre-cooked list facts. Stored both directions (the .p0 reader is line-oriented),
% so the relation resolves regardless of argument order. NB: Germany does NOT
% border Italy (a prior fact was wrong and is removed). ---

% --- gen235 (LLMSCORE): kind-level taxonomy for generic questions like
% "is a dog a mammal or a reptile?" Kept separate from entity facts y(x).

% --- gen235 (LLMSCORE): tiny narrative continuation substrate.
% gen254: the scene word itself and near-synonyms must also bind the scene.
% --- gen240 (LLMSCORE): more scene cues so common story openings continue.
% gen240: a lone watcher / lookout scene (lighthouse, cliff, shore, tower).
% gen240: an enchanted-object scene (book, shelf, mirror, attic, library).
% gen240: a moonlit-garden magical scene.
% gen245: voyage scene for sailor/deck continuations; same scene engine.
% gen254: a rainfall scene ("Raindrops tap the pond" and kin). The cue words are
% base forms; compounds (raindrops, rainfall) bind through the morphological
% prefix rule in the engine, so no alias facts are needed.
% gen254: story-capable scenes — their continuation_template clauses stand alone,
% so "tell me a story about X" can chain them. Verb-phrase scenes (magical,
% voyage) are deliberately absent: their templates need a subject stem.
% gen254: a traveler-at-dusk scene ("when the last light faded from the horizon,
% the traveler realized..."). Three templates so "in three different ways"
% requests have full cardinality; each reads as a clause after "realized".
% gen246: reveal scene for "the old door creaked open to reveal...".
% gen247: mysterious-box scene for clockmaker-style story continuations.

% --- gen235 (LLMSCORE): historically grounded guest-list substrate.
% --- gen236 (LLMSCORE): small lexical/physical commons.

% gen240 (LLMSCORE): two-line rhyming poems as KB knowledge, one per concept.
% The C assembler only selects by topic word; teaching a new couplet extends it.
% gen241 (LLMSCORE-check): more couplet themes the bench asked for. Same engine.

% gen241 (LLMSCORE-check): "a place where you might see X" -> the place. place_for(
% Thing, "a place"). Answers the definition half of riddles like "...means a place
% where you might see exotic animals" -> a zoo. KB-first: add a fact, extend for free.

% gen241 (LLMSCORE-check): roleplay scenario advice as ordered KB steps. "As a store
% manager, what would you do?" -> a measured, grounded answer. The C prefaces an honest
% "I'm not really a manager, but" and lists the steps; adding a scenario is just facts.

% gen241 (LLMSCORE-check): more sentence-completion scenes, so common openers
% ("Tomorrow I plan to...", "Without music, life would...") complete instead of
% refusing. Same scene_cue/continuation_template engine.

% gen241 (LLMSCORE-check): exact-length completions for "complete this in exactly N
% words". completion_exact(Scene, N, "phrase") where the phrase has exactly N words.
% The C counts and verifies the length before using it, so the constraint is honoured.

% gen241 (LLMSCORE-check): three-word fill-in-the-blank values ("...and always ___
% ___ ___"). fill_three("phrase") with exactly three words; the C verifies the count.

% gen245: constrained sensory descriptions. sensory_phrase(Topic, N, "phrase")
% stores exact word-count phrases; sensory_topic maps prompts to the topic.

% gen247: exact-word explanations. concise_explain(Topic, N, "phrase") stores
% phrases whose word count is part of the fact.

% gen241 (LLMSCORE-check): four-line poems (quatrains). Each line is a separate
% poem4(Concept, "line") fact (KB atoms cap at 128 chars), kept in order; the C reads
% the four lines for the topic and joins them. "write a four-line poem about a
% lighthouse" selects by topic word (engine fixed, lexicon learns).

% gen241 (LLMSCORE-check): primary colours as a category, so "name three primary
% colors" resolves through mod_namestart's multi-pick path (engine fixed, data grows).

% gen294 (basic-chat cat.52 "Elencazione"): closed sets enumerated by
% mod_namestart. Keyed by the singular head noun the enumerator derives; the
% engine reads category_member/2, so adding a set here extends "list/name the X"
% for free (KB-first). Ordered as they are conventionally recited.
% keyed zodiac_animal so "Chinese zodiac animals" resolves via the compound
% (qualifier+head) lookup — without it the enumerator matched the generic
% category_member(animal, …) and gave a WRONG list (a misclaim, worse than a wall).

% gen241 (LLMSCORE-check): common idioms as KNOWLEDGE. "what does the idiom X mean?"
% reads idiom_meaning(Phrase, "gloss"). The phrase is the key (matched as a substring
% of the turn); teaching a new idiom is one fact, no code edit.

% gen311 (KB-first definitions): the "what does X mean / define X" FRAME is taught
% data, not a C pattern. describe_cue(Cue) lists substrings that mark a description
% request; the concept consumer then reads a wiki_concept(X, domain, "gloss").
% Grow both via autolearn (describe_cue + wiki_concept are whitelisted), no C edit.

% gen241 (LLMSCORE-check): phase-change knowledge. boils_at / freezes_at give the
% temperature and result, so "what happens when you boil water at sea level?" answers
% with both. One fact per substance; the C only selects by the verb + substance.

% gen241 (LLMSCORE-check): historical facts as KB knowledge. "what year did WWII end,
% and where was the surrender?" reads one phrase that answers both halves.

% gen241 (LLMSCORE-check): population magnitude (approximate present-day order) so
% "which country has the most people?" is answered by comparing ranks, not memorized.

% gen241 (LLMSCORE-check): geography for compound capital questions. The capital
% handler answers the first half from capital_of_country/2 and appends the river or
% the ocean-to-the-west when the turn asks for it. One fact per city/country.
% gen255: kinship as COMPOSABLE knowledge. kinship_level(Rel, N) is how many
% generations Rel stands ABOVE the possessor ("Anna is Maria's grandmother" ->
% 2); kinship_gender(Rel, G) types the ancestor; kinship_name(N, G, Surface)
% maps a summed chain back to language. The C solver only parses "X is Y's R"
% links and adds levels — the lexicon extends here, no code edit.

% gen255: weekday arithmetic substrate — day_order(Day, Index 1..7).

% gen255: DIRECTIONAL borders — border_dir(Country, Direction, Neighbour).
% The generic borders/2 list stays; a direction word in the turn filters here.

% gen254: riddle SIGNATURES — riddle_sig(Id, "cue") lists the substrings that
% must all occur for response_template(Id, ...) in responses.p0 to answer.
% World knowledge (which riddles exist), so it lives here; teaching a riddle
% is facts only, no C branch.
% gen308: riddles distributed from kb/learning/autolearn.p0 (answers in responses.p0).
% gen311 (LLMSCORE): common PROVERB completion reuses the riddle mechanism (cue
% substrings of the beginning -> the full saying). Two cues per proverb, one per line.

% gen311 (LLMSCORE): common 'explain why X' answers, via the riddle mechanism.

% gen311 (riddles-as-inference, F.): a riddle is an EQUATION solved by inference,
% not a memorized cue->answer. The clue verbs map to constraint predicates that are
% RULES over world knowledge; the answer is the inanimate entity satisfying every
% clue. "no voice, yet I cry ... no eyes, yet I flash in the dark" -> a storm.
% Curated here are the bridging rules + seed property/metaphor facts; autolearn grows
% the FACTS (clue_verb/emits/is_like/inanimate are the teachable layer, not the rules).
% gen311 (U1, riddles-as-inference): "I have A but no B" = depicts(X,A) ∧ ¬contains(X,B).
% The negation is load-bearing: a map DEPICTS cities/mountains/water but does not
% CONTAIN houses/trees/fish, while a real country depicts AND contains them — so the
% ¬contains constraint is what picks the map. Grow depicts/contains via autolearn.
% gen311 (U1 extension): "has X but cannot Y / is X but not Y" = has_part(X,·) ∧
% has_property(X,·) ∧ ¬can_do(X,·). "has an eye but cannot see, is sharp but not
% alive" -> a needle; "has hands but can't clap" -> a clock. Load-bearing negation:
% a clock has hands but ¬can_do clap, a person has hands AND can_do clap.
% gen254: named role holders — role_holder(KeyPhrase, "answer"), matched as a
% substring of the turn ("who was the first president of the united states?").
% Teaching a new role is one fact.
% gen254: the year a capital took the role (one fact per country).
% gen254: which city a capital replaced in that role (one fact per country).

% gen241 (LLMSCORE-check): moons, so "name the largest planet and describe one of its
% moons" answers both halves. moon_of(Planet, "Name", "description").

% gen241 (LLMSCORE-check): anagram knowledge. "rearrange the letters in X" reads
% anagram_of(Word, "Result"); the C verifies the letters genuinely match before
% answering, so the fact is checked, never blindly trusted.
% gen311 (LLMSCORE): common anagrams (the C verifies the letters genuinely match).

% gen241/gen244 (LLMSCORE-check + NEXTMOVE): step-by-step procedures as ordered KB
% facts. process_topic/2 is the KB-side bridge from request words to a Task;
% process_step(Task, N, "step") is the content. Adding a task is just more facts --
% the C only selects by topic overlap, orders, and numbers the steps.
% gen311 (KB-first morphology): person-indexed verb forms + pro-drop declaration.
% The translate composer emits the conjugated form for a subject+verb and, where
% pro_drop holds, drops the subject: "I need help" -> "Necesito ayuda". Grow this
% table via autolearn (conj_es/pro_drop are whitelisted), never a C conjugator.
% negation marker: "I don't understand" -> (drop I) + no + entiendo = "No entiendo".
% French subject "you" is "vous" (tr_fr(you, te) is the OBJECT clitic form).
% gen311: interrogative preposition-fronting + copula conjugation. "Where are you
% from?" -> front "from"->"de", de-invert "are you"->"you are", conj_es(are,you,eres)
% + pro-drop -> "de dónde eres". wh_front_es(prep, spanish_prep) is teachable.
% French keeps the subject but elides it before a vowel (elide_fr(je, j') in
% grammar.p0); the progressive aux is dropped (aux_progressive/1). "I am learning
% French" -> "j'apprends français" from conj_fr + tr_fr(french) + those rules.

% gen244 (NEXTMOVE): everyday recommendations as KB-backed activity steps. The
% advice engine selects a situation by activity_topic/2 and renders activity_step/3;
% unknown situations get a scoped gap instead of a blind wall.

% gen241 (LLMSCORE-check): parametric limerick. A limerick is a fixed AABBA form; the
% five image lines per theme live in the KB (engine fixed, lexicon learns). The C only
% joins limerick_l1..l5(Theme).

% Minimal ES lexicon for short translation prompts.
% gen240: more ES glosses for short translation prompts.
% --- gen237 (LLMSCORE): additional common facts and lightweight creative forms.


% gen240 (LLMSCORE): parrot0 has no real preferences, but when asked to pick a
% favourite it offers one honestly rather than dodging. The pick is KB data.
% gen240: honest picks for "what's your favorite <X>" (weather, season, ...).
% gen254: more hypothetical-desire topics from live LLMSCORE probes.

% gen240 (LLMSCORE): appearance/2 lets parrot0 DESCRIBE something it cannot see.
% Asked "describe what a sunset looks like", it admits it has no senses but gives
% the description from KB knowledge (engine fixed, lexicon grows).
% gen240: colours, so "describe blue to someone who has never seen it" works.


% gen245: library haiku images extend the same KB-only haiku assembler.

% gen240 (LLMSCORE): compound-word riddles. compound_word(First, Second, Whole) —
% "the word that follows fire and precedes place" -> fireplace.

% --- gen240 (LLMSCORE): parametric haiku. A haiku is a fixed 5-7-5 structure;
% the poetic image LINES are KB knowledge, pre-syllable-counted, one per concept
% per slot (open=5, mid=7, close=5). The C assembler weaves open(subject) /
% mid(object) / close(subject), so teaching a new concept's three lines extends
% the generator with no code edit (PRINCIPLES.md: engine fixed, lexicon learns).
% gen254: technology and autumn, so paired-theme prompts ("autumn and
% technology") can weave open(subj)/mid(obj)/close(subj) across both.
% gen240: broader haiku lexicon so more requested themes compose (engine fixed).


% gen308: autolearn's verified knowledge, made OFFICIAL (F.'s directive: what
% autolearn learns must be committed as project knowledge). These closed
% "engine_gap" entries in kb/learning/autolearn-ledger.jsonl by pairing a taught
% relation with an answer_frame/2 (gen306) — the CONSUMER-gap reduction: the fact
% alone was inert; the frame makes the question form answerable, no C module.
% Distributed here from the scratch file kb/learning/autolearn.p0 (now deleted);
% chemical_symbol was normalized to one canonical order (Symbol, Element) — the
% scratch file had both directions — and deduplicated.
% the only mammal capable of true flight (bats). rel + answer_frame so the
% "what is the only mammal capable of true flight?" phrasing is answerable.
% capital_on_river(Capital, River): which capital a river runs through.
% gen309: more rivers so the SUPERLATIVE aggregation is meaningful (the Danube
% flows through 4 national capitals, the most of any river in the world).
% "which river runs through the most capital cities?" — a fold over the relation:
% group by River (second arg), count capitals, take the max. aggregate_frame is
% the teachable datum; mod_aggregate supplies only the bounded counting.
% hardest_natural_substance(Substance, Where); the frame answers "what is the
% hardest natural substance on earth?" via the word "earth" -> diamond.

